The test suite `singletest.py` does not appear to work with windows 8.

The issue seems to be with Serial, which all of the tests rely on. 

After the test suite resets the target, the response received on serial is as follows:

`HOST: Unknown property:`

When viewed through a serial terminal:

```
{{timeout;5}}
{{host_test_name;hello_auto}}
{{description;Hello World}}
{{test_id;MBED_10}}
{{start}}
Hello World
[00]{{timeout;5}}
{{host_test_name;hello_auto}}
{{description;Hello World}}
{{test_id;MBED_10}}
{{start}}
Hello World
```

Replicating the same build environment on a windows 7 machine, all tests run successfully.

It could be a symptom of the virtual machine however...

I am running windows 8 on the VMware box, but my serial terminal can see it, why can't the script?

The `SPI::write` method calls `aquire` to ensure that its frequency/mode settings are the current settings in use. However, on the LPC1549, changing the frequency/mode generates a couple of spurious clock edges. If hardware slave select is not used, this can cause the first SPI write that resets the frequency to generate extra clock edges while the slave select is asserted, which can confuse the slave device.

For example, consider the following code run in a loop

```
cs = 1;
spi.write(0x55);
cs = 0;
other_cs = 0;
other_spi.write(0x55);
other_cs = 1;
```

This results in the following logic analyzer trace:
![spi_aquire_glitch_simple](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1348448/8796287/7d3f6a5c-2f48-11e5-8472-84eb4c966930.png)

The extra clock edges causes the analyzer to misread 0x55 as 0xD5 because the first two bits are read  while the SPI peripheral is being reconfigured. The actual 8 bits of data are shifted over by two.

In this case, the two SPI objects are using the same peripheral, but the logic in aquire doesn't care if the two peripherals are the same, so this problem could just as easily occur if the two objects used different peripherals.
